{% extends "layouts/standard_content.jinja" %}
{% from "components/heading.jinja" import heading %}
{% from "components/card.jinja" import card %}
{% from "components/contents.jinja" import contents %}
{% from "components/link.jinja" import link %}
{% from "components/list.jinja" import list, list_item %}
{% block mobile_article_title %}
  {% call heading() %}
    Reading judgments
  {% endcall %}
{% endblock mobile_article_title %}
{% block desktop_article_title %}
  {% call heading() %}
    Reading judgments
  {% endcall %}
{% endblock desktop_article_title %}
{% block article_navigation %}
  {% call contents(title="On this page") %}
    {% call list() %}
      {% call list_item() %}
        {% call link(href="#what-youll-learn") %}
          What you'll learn
        {% endcall %}
      {% endcall %}
      {% call list_item() %}
        {% call link(href="#why-judgment-structure-matters") %}
          Why judgment structure matters
        {% endcall %}
      {% endcall %}
      {% call list_item() %}
        {% call link(href="#getting-started-with-reading-judgments") %}
          Getting started with reading judgments
        {% endcall %}
      {% endcall %}
    {% endcall %}
  {% endcall %}
{% endblock article_navigation %}
{% block article_content %}
  <p>
    Court judgments can seem complicated if you haven't read them before. We’ll help you
    understand how judgments are structured and how to find the information you need.
  </p>
  {% call heading(tag="h2") %}
    What you'll learn
  {% endcall %}
  <p>
    Court judgments follow common patterns and structures. Once you understand these patterns, reading any judgment is easier.
  </p>
  <p>
    {% call link(href=url("understanding_judgments_and_decisions")) %}
      Understanding judgments and decisions
    {% endcall %}
    explains:
  </p>
  {% call list(variant="bullets") %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      the typical structure of a judgment
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      how judges present their reasoning
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      understanding the outcome and orders
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      reading legal citations and references
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      different types of decisions and what they mean
    {% endcall %}
  {% endcall %}
  {% call heading(tag="h2") %}
    Why judgment structure matters
  {% endcall %}
  <p>Judges write judgments to explain their decisions and reasoning. Understanding the structure helps you:</p>
  {% call list(variant="bullets") %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      find the key information quickly
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      follow the judge's legal reasoning
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      understand how the law applies to the case
    {% endcall %}
    {% call list_item() %}
      see which parts are binding precedent
    {% endcall %}
  {% endcall %}
  {% call card(title="Getting started with reading judgments", title_tag="h2", variant="unbordered") %}
    <p>
      If you're reading a judgment for the first time, start with
      {% call link(href=url("understanding_judgments_and_decisions")) %}
        Understanding judgments and decisions
      {% endcall %}
      . This guide takes you through a judgment section by section, explaining what each part contains and why it matters.
    </p>
  {% endcall %}
  {% call card(title="If you’re already familiar with judgments", title_tag="h3") %}
    <p>
      You can go straight to
      {% call link(href=url("search_and_browse")) %}
        Search and Browse
      {% endcall %}
      to find the cases you need.
    </p>
  {% endcall %}
{% endblock article_content %}
